metadata.name: Timing #150
metadata.description:
Time.. 
While one thing happens one time, another happens several times.

----------------------------------------------------------------
  Keys control:
    r: toggle rotation
    i: increment rotation speed
    d: decrement rotation speed
    p: toggle show points
    s: save current size image to .png
    x + 2/4/8: save 2x/4x/8x size image to .png
    1-9 + g: save 1-9 sec animation to .gif (depends on the machine resources)

  URL parameters:
    fps=<value>: frame rate
    r=true: rotation ON
    p=false: do not show points

metadata.name: terrains #213
metadata.description:
A generative set of imaginary landscapes.

Terrains continues a study of topographic media translations that began with Plastic Landscapes (2016) and our Field Guide to Martian Landscapes (2017). While the Field Guide focused on analyzing topographies of another planet, interpreted through telescopic imaging and software translation, this project focuses on the procedural generation of nonexistent landscapes. These landscapes are generated through a complex manipulation of perlin noise, a recurring algorithm used in videogames, film VFX, and generative art since the 1980s that resembles natural geological formations. By no means new, this tradition is part of a lineage of digital visualization projects focused on reproducing nature through algorithmic means. Our algorithm generates sequential bands of noise mapped on an X-Y plane, rendered in an oblique architectural projection, a techniques that comes from technical drawing conventions. This perspective produces a layering effect that flattens the terrain in an architectural way. Neither realistic nor completely abstract, the system plays with projection, entropy, and constraints to produce a collection of imaginary terrains sited on the Tezos blockchain.

We must also credit all who have explored this field of work: Ken Perlin, James M. Bardeen, Stephen Schmitt, Paul Bourke, Joseph Claghorn, Amit Patel, Inigo Quilez, Matt DesLauriers, and many many more...

Press "s" to download PNG.
Press "r" to redraw and shift stripes.

Built with p5.js
By office ca
2023

metadata.name: Flowingcles #87
metadata.description:
"Flowingcles" is a generative art piece that showcases a mesmerizing collection of  circles and abstract shapes. This unique collection invites art enthusiasts to embark on an inspiring visual journey.

Some pieces feature abstract shapes accompanied by a noise effect, reflecting restlessness and energy, while others present a more serene atmosphere with minimalized noise effects. These two approaches offer collectors the freedom to choose the one that resonates with them the most.

The "Flowingcles" collection consists of a total of 128 original pieces. Each artwork has been generated with a unique combination, ensuring individuality and distinctiveness. By incorporating these pieces into their collections, art enthusiasts can adorn their homes, offices, or galleries with a sense of unparalleled art experience and authenticity.

"Flowingcles" stands as a prominent example of modern art, showcasing dynamism, aesthetics, and originality. This collection pushes the boundaries of art and takes viewers on a captivating visual journey. Therefore, me invite art lovers to explore the "Flowingcles" collection and become a part of this visual spectacle:)

- S: Save a png file with the current resolution (2400*3400)
